==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Murder
<hw>Mur"der</hw> <pr>(m⟦ucir⟧r"d⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>morder</ets>, <ets>morther</ets>, AS. <ets>mor⟦edh⟧or</ets>, fr.
<ets>mor⟦edh⟧</ets> murder; akin to D. <ets>moord</ets>, OS.
<ets>mor⟦edh⟧</ets>, G., Dan., & Sw. <ets>mord</ets>, Icel.
<ets>mor⟦edh⟧</ets>, Goth. <ets>ma⟦uacute⟧r⟦thorn⟧r</ets>, OSlav.
<ets>mr⟦emac⟧ti</ets> to die, Lith. <ets>mirti</ets>, W. <ets>marw</ets>
dead, L. <ets>mors</ets>, <ets>mortis</ets>, death, <ets>mori</ets>,
<ets>moriri</ets>, to die, Gr. <grk>broto`s</grk> (for
<grk>mroto`s</grk>) mortal, <grk>'a`mbrotos</grk> immortal, Skr.
<ets>m⟦rsdot⟧</ets> to die, <ets>m⟦rsdot⟧ta</ets> death. ⟦root⟧105. Cf.
<er>Amaranth</er>, <er>Ambrosia</er>, <er>Mortal</er>.]</ety> <def>The
offense of killing a human being with malice prepense or aforethought,
express or implied; intentional and unlawful homicide.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Mordre</xex> will out.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The killing of their children had, in the account of God, the
guilt of <qex>murder</qex>, as the offering them to idols had the guilt
of idolatry.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Slaughter grows <qex>murder</qex> when it goes too far.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Murder in the second degree</xex>, in most
jurisdictions, is a malicious homicide committed without a specific
intention to take life.</note> <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Murder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Murder
<hw>Mur"der</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Murdered</conjf> <pr>(m⟦ucir⟧r"d⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Murdering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>mortheren</ets>, <ets>murtheren</ets>, AS. <ets>myr⟦edh⟧rian</ets>;
akin to OHG. <ets>murdiren</ets>, Goth.
<ets>ma⟦uacute⟧r⟦thorn⟧rjan</ets>. See <er>Murder</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To kill with premediated malice;
to kill (a human being) willfully, deliberately, and unlawfully. See
<er>Murder</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To destroy; to put an end to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Canst thou] <qex>murder</qex> thy breath in middle of a word?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To mutilate, spoil, or deform, as if with malice or
cruelty; to mangle; <as>as, to <ex>murder</ex> the king's
English</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To kill; assassinate; slay. See
<er>Kill</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>murdered</ent>⟦br⟧
